{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_brookland_ver01/data/sn84026749/00222254632/1930091001/0968.xml":{"full_text":"Motorization of Washington\u2019s\nPolice Department\nJ Lyi.iiti llw\nComplete motorization of the Second precinct of Washing\nton\u2019s police department will be followed by the same process in\nother precincts if the Commissioner in charge and high police\nofficials have their way. Until that is done, some automobiles\nwill be used in all precincts. It is, in the opinion of police\nheads, progress. Unless motorization x fails to accomplish the\nsuccesses expected, the old style of foot patrols will ultimately\nalmost disappear here.\nThere' is still much conflict throughout the country between\nadvocates of old-time police methods and the advanced leaders\nwho hold that modern crime and criminals can only be re\nstricted by scientific crime detection through the utilization of\nscientists, scientific methods and instruments.\nMotorization, in connection with radio transmission, is one\nadvance recommended. Another which Washington police\nheads will seek is scientific crime laboratories, in which tech\nnicians are said to accomplish wonders.\nForty American cities are now using radio in rapid crime\nwork. Policemen patroling beats in automobiles are radio\nequipped. A central police radio station conveys to them in\nstant messages and there are instances in which these modern\ndevices have enabled policemen to arrest burglars before they\nleft their jobs and to capture murderers before their victims\nwere cold.\nTn the next budget the Commissioners will ask Congress for\nfunds to put radio to work in the Washington department and\nthere is little doubt these appropriations will be given.\nThere is an ambitious program for Washington\u2019s police de\npartment, and one thing will be the professional training of po\nlicemen in scientific ways of crime detection. Brawn and bulk\nwill not be objected to in the police personnel, but with it must\nbe intelligence.\n\nBridging Chesapeake Bay\nThe Chesapeake Bay Bridge Commission, appointed by Gov\nernor Ritchie, has begun studies of methods to connect the\neastern and western shores of Chesapeake Bay by a bridge.\nEngineering surveys will be made.\nIt will not be many years before there is a bridge spanning\nthe waters of the bay. Increasing traffic will make it neces\nsary. The State does not now wish to undertake the job,\nwhich will, it is estimated, cost between $10,000,000 and $12,-\n000,000, and efforts will continue to interest private capital,\nheretofore considering the matter.\nLarge numbers of Washington people, frequent visitors to\nall parts of Chesapeake Bay, are interested in the proposed\nventure. If constructed by private capital there would be toll\ncharges, but these would be less than ferry charges now made\non machines and passengers. Much time would be saved over\nferry processes.\nMysteries of Science\nSome of the scientific\ntheories and discoveries of\nmodem times have caused\nmen, at moments, to question\nwhether, after all, nature is\nnot. perhaps, capricious and\nillogical. Are natural laws as\nimmutable as the laws of the\nMedes and Persians? Are laws\nwhich hold true everywhere\non earth likewise valid on Bet\nelgeuse or Sirius?\nIt was the Norwegian dram\natist, Ibsen, who once asked:\n\u201cHow can you guarantee that\ntwo and two do not make five\non Jupiter?\u201d 4\nIn modem times the discov-x\nery of the non-Euclidean geom\netries brings forcibly to the\nforeground this very question.\nIs the Euclidean geometry\n\u201ctrue\u201d on this planet, but not\n\u201ctrue\u201d on Mars? Huxley,\nthough no mathematician and\nnot having the mathemati\ncian\u2019s point of view, sensed the\nimportance of the issue, as illus\ntrated in his words:\n\u201cLet us suppose that a tele\nscope powerful enough to show\nus what is going on in the\nnebula of the Sword of Orion\nshould reveal g world in which\n4 stones fell upward, parallel\nlines met and the fourth di\nmension of space was quite\nobvious.\u201d\nMen of science would have\nonly two alternatives before\nthem. Either the terrestrial\nand the nebular facts must be\nbrought into harmony by such\nfeats of subtle sophistry as the\nhuman mind is always capable\nof performing when driven into\nHearst Papers Advocate\n1. \"Peace and amity with all nations; entangling\nalliances with none,\" as advocated by George\nWashington.\n2. Proportional representation in the United States\nSenate, no State to have less than two Senators.\nLegislation to enforce prompt constitutional reap\nportionment in the House of Representatives.\n3. A separate Department of the Army, of the Navy\nand of the Air Forces, all united under a Secre\ntary of National Defense.\n4. Federal action to the limit of Federal poioers to\nabolish illiteracy in the United States under a\nSecretary of Education.\n5. Installation of the President on the first of Jan\nuary following November election.\n6. Selective immigration to admit only those suitea\nfor American citizenship.\n7. Deportation of undesirable aliens.\n8. Complete publicity for income taxes.\nEDITORIAL PAGE\nOF THE\nBy Archibald Henderson\na comer; or science must throw\ndown its aims in despair and\ncommit suicide, either by the\nadmission that the universe is,\nafter all, irrational, inasmuch\nas that which is truth in one\ncorner of it is absurdity in an\nother, or by a declaration of\nincompetency.\nEinstein has shown conclu\nsively that Huxley is wrong and\nthat neither geometry is \u201ctrue\u201d\nin the absolute sense. The par\nticular geometry most suitable\nis that- determined by the\nmetric properties of the particu\nlar space in question. Fortu\nnately, these geometries were\navailable to him through the\ndiscoveries of a young Hun\ngarian, Janos Bolyai.\nThis young man (1802-1860),\nwhose father was a fellow stu\ndent at Goettingen of the great\nmathematician Gauss, produced\na brief treatise on \u201cthe abso\nlutely true science of space,\u201d as\nhe called it.\nIn his enthusiasm he wrote\nhis father: \u201cI have created a\nnew universe from nothing.\u201d\nIn contradistinction to Euclid,\nBolyai assumed that, in a plane,\ninstead of one line, two lines\ncould be drawn through a point\nparallel to a given line.\nThe system thus set up was\nlogical and self consistent.\nGauss wrote in 1832: \u201cI con\nsider the young geometer, Von\nBolyai, a genius of the first\nrank.\u201d Bolyai\u2019s epochal work\nis one of the most brilliant\nachievements in the history of\nscience.\n(Copyright. 1030, International Feature\nService, Inc.)\nWA S HJNGXDN.. TIM E S\nI See By the Papers By t. e; Powers\nUP IN MAIHE. ELECT!OM g|\n\\AA\\ *7) a f rT J\nA AM A I BKICKfI h\n\\q, J a\\ I F&S&mZ'i\nO Ih cometax\nAS EE So UR\n1 -Mr\nSc\n457 0 sSv\u2014 W)\n\\c-Z G iwl\nLetters to the Editor From Readers of The Times\nWriter Questions Hoover\nPolicy on Unemployment\nEditor. Times:\nRepresentative William E.\nHull of Illinois issues through\nthe Republican national com\nmittee a statement which* says,\nin part:\nThe President secured an\nagreement from the employers\nof labor that they (the em\nployers) would not reduce\nwages. If it had not been for\nPresident Hoover\u2019s quick action\na panic might have occurred.\nIn the face of this very com\nmendable action of the Presi\ndent and agreement of employ\ners of labor, how are the people\nand government employes af\nfected. right here in Washing\nton, to account for the follow\ning. to-wit:\nFirst\u2014The loss of two years of\none \u201cstep-up\u201d pay, from Jul y 1.\n1928. to July 1, 1930. that the\nCongress intended should be two\n\u201cstep-up\u201d pay beginning July 1,\n1928\nFurther: When the Brookhart\nbill passed the Senate unani\nmously, January 6, 1930, and\nwas reported to the House Janu\nary 11, 1930, Mr. Lehlbach had\neliminated, by amendment, the\nretroactive back-pay for two\nyears for the one \u201cstep-up\u201d that\nthe low-salaried employes were\ndeprived of while all other gov\nernment higher-paid employes,\naffected by the Welch bill, as of\nJuly 1, 1928. benefited in full\nof the two \u201cstep-up.\u201d Why this\nflesh of the higher-paid and fish\nof the lower-paid?\nThe Lehlbach amendment to\nthe Brookhart bill legally took\n$240 from the one steppers-up\nof 1928. But again:, not satis\nfied with this legal theft the\nBureau of Engraving and Print\ning furloughed many of its\nwomen pay-by-day employes two\ndays a month without pay, so\ntheir loss of two days pay each\nmonth was more than their one\nstep-up pay increase 0f1928.\nNow these same employes,\nmany of them the most expert\nand skilled of the bureau, are\nbeing furloughed three days a\nmonth. So we have this condi\ntion; the same or less wage per\nmonth than before the increased*\ntwo-steps, one-step of 1928 and\nthe one-step of 1930.\nAnd these things taking place\nin the United States Govern\nment departments here in Wash\nington in face of and defiance\nof President Hoover\u2019s requests\nof labor employers not to reduce\nwages and the employers*\npromise not to.\nOne may call out on the\nhousetops: Uncle Sam cure thy\nself, for* he who had not, the\nlittle he had you have taken\nfrom him.\nW. E. RYAN,\n3126 Sixteenth St. N. W.\nCalls Upon Citizens\nJtor Bicentennial Drive\nEditor. Times:\nThe associate directors of the\nUnited States commission for\nthe celebration of the 200th an\nniversary of the birth of George\nWashington, in a recent letter\nin your columns, make a state\nment that is of great impor-\ntance to the District of Colum\nbia and the National Capital.\nIn speaking of the plans for\nthe great celebrations of 1932\nthey say: \u201cThere is to be no\nconcentration of effort in be\nhalf of the National Capital.\u201d\nThat is a statement of their\nwork and their purpose, and\nthat is correct. I hope every\ncitizen of the District of Co\nlumbia has read it. It makes\nclear that all the great events\nin the District of Columbia in\n1932 in the city Washington\nListen, World!\nBy Elsie Robinson\nAll this talk about farm re\nlief. Bad times in the country\ndistricts.. .heck to pay in Wash\nington. Why? Is it because\ndirt\u2019s cussed, climate contrary\nand trading crooked? Or is\nthere possibly something amiss\nwith Si himself?\nNow, mind you, I\u2019ve nothing\nagainst farmers, per se. I\u2019m\none myse'.f and 100 per cent\nstrong for the racket. Yet if\nyou nose around you can\u2019t help\nnoticing things and\u2014well, here\nare some facts. Judge for your\nself:\nI\u2019m working 400 acres of the\nprettiest dirt you'd want to find.\nFine water. Perfect climate. A\nhunk of heaven\u2014with similar\nhunks all around for a hundred\nmiles. You couldn\u2019t locate a\nnicer ranching district. Yet it\u2019s\nthe same old story. Dilapidated\nbuildings. Starving cattle and\nskimpy crops. Banks foreclos\ning. Young, husky men loafing\naround, discouraged and dis\ngusted. Riding past the broken\nfences, surveying the weed\ngrown orchards. I\u2019ve wondered.\n\"No market\u2014what\u2019s the use\nof working?\u201d they answered.\nWas that eally the reason?\nThe day I rode into the\nbusy little town thavs the cen\nter of our district. Things looked\nprosperous enough. Radios blar\ning under the awnings, cars\nparked along the curb. Sun\ntanned young bucks striding\naround in trick Stetsons. Made\nme think of my own young\nsters, out oh the ranch. Six of\nthe finest Born ranchers, but\nwith no more notion of modem\nmethods than a bunch of\ngophers. I decided I\u2019d take back\nan armful of farm magazines\u2014\nstart reading up. Should be\neasy enough to get them, with\nthree drug stores to choose\nfrom.\nEasy? In ten minutes\nlearned plenty. Buy a farm\nmagazine in a ranching com\nmunity? Try and do it! Maga\nzines enough\u2014racks piled high\nwith them\u2014but what about?\nLove stories, detectives stories,\nwild West romances, confes\nsions\u2014but nary a page on cat\ntle or grain.\n\u201cIt\u2019s no use carrying them\u2014\nwe wouldn\u2019t have a call for one\nin a year,\u201d smiled the three\nproprietors.\n\u201cBut how about the men?\nSurely the farmers, themselves,\ndon\u2019t read this stuff?\u201d\nfounded and amid the scenes of\nhis life and death\u2014these events\nthat must express the honor\nand reverence of. the entire na\ntion\u2014depend entirely upon the\nDistrict of Columbia George\nWashington Bicentennial Com\nmission. If the United States\ncommission will make, no con\ncentration of effort in behalf\nof the National Capital, we\nmust.\nMany times our citizens have\nasked the difference between\nthe United States commission\n\u201cYes, they do. Just as crazy\nabout it as the women. And\nyou can't blame them. It\u2019s\nsort of a relaxation\nRelaxation? From what? From\nthe grind of futile drudgery?\nBut what makes it futile and\nwhat makes it drudgery? The\ncussedness of climate, the crook\nedness of markets? Or their\nown ignorance and indifference\nand lack of enthusiasm? Read\ning love confessions and wild\nWest heart throbs while the\nwheat dwindles in the sour soil\nof the south pasture, while\ntheir fruit trees die of blight,\nbecause they try to run their\nfarms by methods which their\ngranddads used?\nCould a business man keep\nhis trade if he showed no more\ninterest than that? Could an\neditor run his paper if he did\nno more studying than that?\nJudge for yourself.\n(Copyright. 193\". King Features\nSyndicate, Inc.)\nKNOWLEDGE\nTEST\nDo you know:\n1. What is an escalato?r\n2. What is the ordinary\nname for fleur-de-lis?\n3. What is the character\nistic of the Gothic arch?\n4. In Greek mythology, what\nname was given to the\ngarden of the golden\napples?\n5. What crime is lese maj\neste?\nMatch correctly:\n6. indignity\nendorsement\n7. reduce\n\u00fcbiauitous\n8. enervate\naffront\n9. omnipresent\nweaken\n10. sanction\ndiminish\nFin each blank:\n11. The Mason and Dixons\nline is the southern bound\nary of\n12. A pedestrian is a\ntraveler.\n13. An amateur is one rated\nnot as a\n14. A gourmand is a luxurious\n15. Hesperus is the evening\n(Answera on Magaxine Page.)\nand the District of Columbia\ncommission in this work. This\nletter of Col. U. S. Grant 3d\nand Representative Sol\nBloom makes this perfectly\nclear. It is their business to\ncreate a nation-wide Washing\nton consciousness. Our busi\nness is to put over the great\nprogram in Washington which\nwill express that consciousness\nto the nations of the world.\nThis is why the responsibility\nof the District of Columbia\nBicentennial Commission is\ngreat. Every loyal citizen of\nthe District ought to support\nits work and give their entire\nmoral support and all the\nfinancial help possible.\nThe United States commis\nsion has a large suit of offices,\na large staff, a large appropria\ntion from Congress. The Dis\ntrict of Columbia commission\nhas the largest task and the\nDistrict of Columbia has a\nsmall office, small staff, and\nno appropriation. It is de\npendent upon the voluntary\ngifts from the loyal citizens of\nthe District. Whatever is done\nin Washington for Washington\nand the nation in 1932 must be\ndone by the District of Colum\nbia commission. Hence, we\nappeal to all the City of Wash\nington an<j the District to\nstand by it in its work.\nFREDERICK V, FISHER,\nExecutive Officer,\nDistrict Commission.\nSECRETS OF\nHEALTH\n\u2014By Dr. Louis E. Bisch\u2014\nAfter the stomach comes the\nintestine, and after that the\nlarge intestine.\nThe small intestine is very\nlong\u2014about 20 feet. Where it\njoins with the stomach it is\nabout 2 inches in diameter and\ngradually its size diminishes un\ntil it is only about 1 inch in\nwidth where it runs? into the\nlarge intestine. It is customary\nto divide the small intestine\ninto three parts\u2014the duodenum,\nthe jejunun and the ileum.\nThe duodenum is a favorite\nplace for ulcers. It is about 8\ninches in length. At first it\nruns upward and then makes a\ncomplete bend.\nThe second division, or jeju\nnun, runs on about IVa feet.\nThe third division or ileum,\nis the most twisted of all, and\noften it is difficult to say just\nwhere the jejenun ends and the\nileum begins.\nThe small intestine is com\nposed of four coats or layers.\nOn the outside is a serous\nfoyer, then there is a muscular\ncoat, then a submucus one and\nlastly a mucous layer.\nFrom the mucous coat there\nextend into the intestinal tube\ntiny, finger-like projections\ncallecl \u201cvilli.\u201d These inrimm\nthe surface and hence abeor>\ntion power of the intestinal\ntract.\nBesides the intestines remain\nglands and nodes of throe types\nThe so-called Meettool\nglands** are everywhere to Me\nsmall as weU an form immbaa.\nLa Follette, FwMMdgMhr\ntl r* 1L\nti Mi\n\nPHILIP LA FOLLETTE. FINE YOUNG MB GT A\nBRILLIANT FATBEB.\nThe late Robert La Follette, Senator from WfooomM. am\nwho worked for the people that elected him. sat Mr eaepam\ntions that needed him, was a successful man to Me My \u00abf bn\ndeath. He was successful because he DID TBB 880 TBST\nWAS IN HIM, which is as great a mcmae m aap anm am\nhave.\nNow he has other success that few mjoy\u2014 mmdy Ml\nCONTINUATION OF USEFUL SERVICE fBMM BB\nCHILDREN.\nThis son of the late Senator La Follette is a obgMMM Mr\nGovernor of Wisconsin. His own gaalftao M|p baa; Ma\nmemory of his father and gratitude for the MflMr'e nMh\nhelp him also.\nHe has a brother, another son of the Into Maaaw \u00abMe\nrepresents his father and his State, in Me Seaata. woMMg\nhis father did for those that elected him.\nHappy is the late La Follette, with two oom Mat haem Ma\nname and respect his example of public service\nSome men would \u201cturn in Meir graves\u2019\u2019 ts Bey caaM\nknow how their sons misuse their iaheritaaee.\nConcerning the late Senator La Follette yea may aw Md\nhe would \u201cSMILE IN HIS GRAVE\u201d if be eeaM haw bam\nworthily his boys represent him.\nThe greatest good fortune for a son a to bane a faM